{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/contraception-sterilization/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"28b2eb26-8068-5798-b284-630c74c6e068","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 8d19337f-a369-4084-ab7b-6acde618875b --><h2>What is sterilization?</h2><!-- end field 8d19337f-a369-4084-ab7b-6acde618875b -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 4124d5a0-122a-4080-91b9-88b4a649dd74 --><!-- begin field 7edae99f-a4b2-4462-9984-17cba1170427 --><ul><li>Sterilization is a permanent method of contraception and includes male or female sterilization.</li><li><strong>Male sterilization </strong>(vasectomy) — the vas deferens is permanently interrupted to ensure sperm cannot enter the ejaculate. <ul><li>Scalpel method — one or two incisions are made in the scrotal skin to expose the vas deferens, which is then occluded and divided.</li><li>Minimally invasive vasectomy (MIV) — a variety of surgical instruments may be used (including a scalpel) to open the skin 10 mm or less to expose the vas deferens. </li><li>Occlusion of the vas deferens is achieved one of three methods:<ul><li>Coagulation/cauterization.</li><li>Ligation with sutures or metal clips.</li><li>Insertion of intra-vas devices or plugs.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li><strong>Female sterilization </strong>(tubal occlusion) — the fallopian tubes are occluded or interrupted to prevent fertliization. <ul><li>Hysteroscopic sterilization — flexible Essure® micro-inserts are passed through a hysteroscope and inserted into the proximal section of each fallopian tube to occlude them.</li><li>Laparoscopic sterilization — Tubal rings or clips (such as Filshie clips) are used to occlude the fallopian tubes, or diathermy can be used to destroy a segment of the fallopian tubes. </li><li>Mini-laparotomy —fallopian tubes can be partially removed and ligated, or occluded with a tubal ring or clip. This is rarely performed, but can be used if laparoscopic access has failed or is contraindicated. </li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/contraception-sterilization/references/\">FSRH, 2014</a>]</p><!-- end field 7edae99f-a4b2-4462-9984-17cba1170427 --><!-- end item 4124d5a0-122a-4080-91b9-88b4a649dd74 -->","topic":{"id":"8476bca2-26f3-58bf-9534-43bcd97620c4","topicId":"687784f1-c4f9-49e1-b81b-030c7fcf147a","topicName":"Contraception - sterilization","slug":"contraception-sterilization","lastRevised":"Last revised in June 2016","chapters":[{"id":"0a0eec74-d846-559b-9873-f4c72e00d5af","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"3180d0e4-2338-5fcd-b4b5-614d98f1acca","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"176d72c6-7d31-5475-9da0-78510905dad1","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"c63caa3e-3aaf-5b63-822c-8ececa2d150b","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"95258b7f-0b95-5dc0-8ffa-c171d269ba0a","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"81b04194-d074-5c40-ba4f-eaa5222ad594","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"d87fe99a-fa45-51e5-82fc-64ac4254370b","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"50d0b72e-30a1-5fe6-b65e-8d6fe12af0f7","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"2574066e-369c-54f1-9929-2706d8798924","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"1080840c-8b97-511c-b653-383403be4bf8","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"198a6919-897f-59e9-83d7-a78a592e6b9c","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - options for local implementation"},{"id":"7a718378-90fe-50b7-9256-240d1ab73099","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{